AGI - "It is not the ideal solution to have them placed in a community but it is better than the conditions in which they were in the caravan with ticks and fleas">. Fabio Galesi, council member of the Pd at the City Hall 8 in Milan, defends himself after the publication of a letter on the 'Corriere della Sera' of today signed by the prize Campiello Giorgio Fontana and another 150 people protesting for the clearing in recent days of B. and H., a couple of elderly and sick people of 88 and 87 years who lived in a caravan in Piazzale Cimitero Maggiore." "During the removal, local police and Amsa - write the citizens - have provided damage, render unusable and remove the caravan, the only housing resource as well as place where they kept their personal effects >. On January 17, Galesi posted a video of the operation on Facebook, claiming it. Afterwards, the video was removed. Given the obvious fragility of the couple it is shameful that the only action put in the field was a clear. It is frustrating to note that the institutions do not coordinate and, as only solutions, involve actions of an aggressive and repressive nature". &nbsp;
"I took the video off because the signatures were being collected and I didn't want to provoke further polemics as many express themselves without knowing the situation," says AGI&nbsp; the leader of the majority driving the city. According to Galesi, it must be taken into account the context: "Before the pandemic was planned the redevelopment of the area of the square of the Cemetery where there are green areas and parking spaces. There were slowdowns because of the increase in costs, then it went on. The last part was missing, the one in the area where the gentlemen were. In these 4 years there have been planned interventions also through social services, offering alternatives to people who were invited to move. No one has been hunted. There were only one family left and the two elders in this caravan who would challenge anyone to define a dignified habitat." &nbsp;
"To the lords was offered only a housing solution in a structure in Ponte Lambro, a year ago - read again in the letter -. With the heavy rains of that time the camp flooded and as soon as possible the two, frightened, asked to return to the Major Cemetery." And from here they had to leave after the intervention of the Municipality despite the opposition also of the daughter.&nbsp; "It's four years that we mediate. Maybe someone's comfortable standing there so the yard doesn't leave. Who? For example, at the social center 'Torchiera' which has never been integrated into the neighborhood, unlike other social centers."
The two elders are now guests of the Ambrosian Centre of Solidarity in the Park Lambro>. "No one has told us," they let the associations that followed the couple in these years. "When they were placed in the Centre - says Galesi - a socio-sanitary worker was also made available to them in addition to the domicile social services". &nbsp;

